                Telewest (Canada) Team
                      for Anathema Uk!

»CL1:CC:»CL0: As well as being a scene musician,
    you have also achieved what is
    perhaps the dream of many a scene
    musician, namely making music for
    games - perhaps you'd give us a
    full round-up on the games that
    feature and will feature your
    music?
»CL3:M!:»CL2: On the Playstation Music front you
    will be hearing my Music on Mortal
    Kombat 4 I am working on that as
    we speak. I did 2 Soundtrack to Mk
    Trilogy (The Subway & Streets
    Stage) and Xenocide! I also work
    with my Uncle friend (David Logan)
    on the Pitfall 3d Tunes! and
    besides that I have signed a
    contract alongside my uncle with
    X-Trax Development which will
    secure my future with playstation
    Musics. On the Snes and Nintendo64
    side, well Double Dragon on the
    Snes featured some of my Dat
    Musics. As for future games, well
    as know, if your under a contract,
    that makes you not to publish,
    discuss or transmit any thing
    which is in development! Sorry the
    only reason why I spoke to you
    about MK4 is because I know the
    team quite well! Hello Barny! Hah,
    Hah

 

»CL1:CC:»CL0: I have heard you are using a new
    Amiga tracker called TeleTracker
    which should be rather cool - so
    perhaps you could explain a bit
    about that?
»CL3:M!:»CL2: Teletracker is developed by
    Telewest Canada! These dudes are
    doing the Atari Falcon conversion
    of Chip Attack 2 for Anathema Uk.
    This production is C64 Emulator
    Music Tracker...It features 4
    track sequences (just like the
    rest...) I was using the
    Beta-Version of this tracker to do
    my C64 conversion. And what a
    remarkable Tracker it is...You can
    develop your own waveform and
    whats good about it is that you
    can play each voice independantly.
    Not like in protracker! it's is
    Portracker supportive, So you can
    load your chip modules into it,
    but you have to select it in a
    menu selector in the program....It
    also supports big modules too, So
    not only it's a C64 Emulator, but
    a Multi-Program which features
    protracker stuff. You can load in
    a loop sample of 155k which is
    better than the protracker version
    which is 64k...The Teletracker
    program takes 150k only, but put
    some of the program in Fast
    Memory, So you have more chip
    Memory to work with ...All
    replayers that work with
    Protracker will not work unless
    you resave it out as a PT tune and
    have the standard M.K to the label
    of your tune! A Nice program it is
    and I am not gonna compare it with
    any other trackers because this is
    where people starts to critise
    each other program and I am not
    into that. The Amiga version will
    be ready in 2/3 months time a beta
    test version is now out! So check
    it out dudes! This Teletracker
    will not be Shareware! All
    prgramming for this Program is
    Written By TZA (The Sucker who
    coded it! Hello Tony!!!!)

